events.description: Vandals, Alans and Suebians cross the Rhine, beginning an invasion of Gaul.
events.html: • 406 – Vandals, Alans and Suebians cross the Rhine, beginning an invasion of Gaul.[2]

events.description: Byzantine general Belisarius completes the conquest of Sicily, defeating the Gothic garrison of Palermo (Panormos), and ending his consulship for the year.
events.html: • 535 – Byzantine general Belisarius completes the conquest of Sicily, defeating the Gothic garrison of Palermo (Panormos), and ending his consulship for the year.[3]

events.description: Battle of Englefield: The Vikings clash with ealdorman Æthelwulf of Berkshire. The invaders are driven back to Reading (East Anglia); many Danes are killed.
events.html: • 870 – Battle of Englefield: The Vikings clash with ealdorman Æthelwulf of Berkshire. The invaders are driven back to Reading (East Anglia); many Danes are killed.[4]

events.description: Holy Roman Emperor Henry IV is forced to abdicate in favor of his son, Henry V, in Ingelheim.
events.html: • 1105 – Holy Roman Emperor Henry IV is forced to abdicate in favor of his son, Henry V, in Ingelheim.[5]

events.description: The Lý dynasty of Vietnam ends after 216 years by the enthronement of the boy emperor Trần Thái Tông, husband of the last Lý monarch, Lý Chiêu Hoàng, starting the Trần dynasty.[citation needed]
events.html: • 1225 – The Lý dynasty of Vietnam ends after 216 years by the enthronement of the boy emperor Trần Thái Tông, husband of the last Lý monarch, Lý Chiêu Hoàng, starting the Trần dynasty.[citation needed][6]

events.description: James I the Conqueror, King of Aragon, enters Medina Mayurqa (now known as Palma, Spain), thus consummating the Christian reconquest of the island of Majorca.
events.html: • 1229 – James I the Conqueror, King of Aragon, enters Medina Mayurqa (now known as Palma, Spain), thus consummating the Christian reconquest of the island of Majorca.[7]

events.description: The First Battle of Cannanore commences, seeing the first use of the naval line of battle.[citation needed]
events.html: • 1501 – The First Battle of Cannanore commences, seeing the first use of the naval line of battle.[citation needed]

events.description: The British East India Company is chartered.
events.html: • 1600 – The British East India Company is chartered.[8]

events.description: James II of England is named Duke of Normandy by Louis XIV of France.
events.html: • 1660 – James II of England is named Duke of Normandy by Louis XIV of France.

events.description: The expedition of John Narborough leaves Corral Bay, having surveyed the coast and lost four hostages to the Spanish.
events.html: • 1670 – The expedition of John Narborough leaves Corral Bay, having surveyed the coast and lost four hostages to the Spanish.[9]

events.description: The first Huguenots set sail from France to the Cape of Good Hope.
events.html: • 1687 – The first Huguenots set sail from France to the Cape of Good Hope.

events.description: Empress Elizabeth I of Russia issues her ukase incorporating Königsberg into Russia.
events.html: • 1757 – Empress Elizabeth I of Russia issues her ukase incorporating Königsberg into Russia.

events.description: Arthur Guinness signs a 9,000-year lease at £45 per annum and starts brewing Guinness.
events.html: • 1759 – Arthur Guinness signs a 9,000-year lease at £45 per annum and starts brewing Guinness.

events.description: American Revolutionary War: Battle of Quebec: British forces under General Guy Carleton repulse an attack by Continental Army General Richard Montgomery in a snowstorm.
events.html: • 1775 – American Revolutionary War: Battle of Quebec: British forces under General Guy Carleton repulse an attack by Continental Army General Richard Montgomery in a snowstorm.[10]

events.description: Efimeris, the oldest Greek newspaper of which issues have survived till today, is published for the first time.
events.html: • 1790 – Efimeris, the oldest Greek newspaper of which issues have survived till today, is published for the first time.

events.description: The incorporation of Baltimore as a city.
events.html: • 1796 – The incorporation of Baltimore as a city.

events.description: Gramercy Park is deeded to New York City.
events.html: • 1831 – Gramercy Park is deeded to New York City.

events.description: The Philippines skipped this date in order to align the country with the rest of Asia, as the trading interest switched to China, Dutch East Indies and neighboring territories after Mexico gained independence from Spain on 27 September 1821. In the islands, Monday, 30 December 1844 was immediately followed by Wednesday, 1 January 1845.
events.html: • 1844 – The Philippines skipped this date in order to align the country with the rest of Asia, as the trading interest switched to China, Dutch East Indies and neighboring territories after Mexico gained independence from Spain on 27 September 1821. In the islands, Monday, 30 December 1844 was immediately followed by Wednesday, 1 January 1845.[11][12]

events.description: A dinner party is held inside a life-size model of an iguanodon created by Benjamin Waterhouse Hawkins and Sir Richard Owen in south London, England.
events.html: • 1853 – A dinner party is held inside a life-size model of an iguanodon created by Benjamin Waterhouse Hawkins and Sir Richard Owen in south London, England.

events.description: Queen Victoria chooses Ottawa, then a small logging town, as the capital of the Province of Canada.
events.html: • 1857 – Queen Victoria chooses Ottawa, then a small logging town, as the capital of the Province of Canada.

events.description: American Civil War: The three-day Battle of Stones River begins near Murfreesboro, Tennessee between the Confederate Army of Tennessee under General Braxton Bragg and the Union Army of the Cumberland under General William S. Rosecrans.
events.html: • 1862 – American Civil War: The three-day Battle of Stones River begins near Murfreesboro, Tennessee between the Confederate Army of Tennessee under General Braxton Bragg and the Union Army of the Cumberland under General William S. Rosecrans.[13][14]

events.description: American Civil War: Abraham Lincoln signs an enabling act that would admit West Virginia to the Union, thus dividing Virginia in two.
events.html: • 1862 – American Civil War: Abraham Lincoln signs an enabling act that would admit West Virginia to the Union, thus dividing Virginia in two.[15]

events.description: Karl Benz, working in Mannheim, Germany, files for a patent on his first reliable two-stroke gas engine. He was granted the patent in 1879.
events.html: • 1878 – Karl Benz, working in Mannheim, Germany, files for a patent on his first reliable two-stroke gas engine. He was granted the patent in 1879.

events.description: Thomas Edison demonstrates incandescent lighting to the public for the first time, in Menlo Park, New Jersey.
events.html: • 1879 – Thomas Edison demonstrates incandescent lighting to the public for the first time, in Menlo Park, New Jersey.

events.description: Mozaffar ad-Din Shah Qajar signs the Persian Constitution of 1906.
events.html: • 1906 – Mozaffar ad-Din Shah Qajar signs the Persian Constitution of 1906.[16]

events.description: The first ever ball drop in Times Square.
events.html: • 1907 – The first ever ball drop in Times Square.[17]

events.description: USS Essex, first aircraft carrier of a 24-ship class, is commissioned.
events.html: • 1942 – USS Essex, first aircraft carrier of a 24-ship class, is commissioned.[18]

events.description: World War II: The Royal Navy defeats the Kriegsmarine at the Battle of the Barents Sea. This leads to the resignation of Grand Admiral Erich Raeder a month later.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: The Royal Navy defeats the Kriegsmarine at the Battle of the Barents Sea. This leads to the resignation of Grand Admiral Erich Raeder a month later.[19]

events.description: World War II: Operation Nordwind, the last major Wehrmacht offensive on the Western Front, begins.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: Operation Nordwind, the last major Wehrmacht offensive on the Western Front, begins.

events.description: President Harry S. Truman officially proclaims the end of hostilities in World War II.
events.html: • 1946 – President Harry S. Truman officially proclaims the end of hostilities in World War II.

events.description: Cold War: The Marshall Plan expires after distributing more than US$13.3 billion in foreign aid to rebuild Western Europe.
events.html: • 1951 – Cold War: The Marshall Plan expires after distributing more than US$13.3 billion in foreign aid to rebuild Western Europe.

events.description: General Motors becomes the first U.S. corporation to make over US$1 billion in a year.
events.html: • 1955 – General Motors becomes the first U.S. corporation to make over US$1 billion in a year.

events.description: The Romanian Television network begins its first broadcast in Bucharest.
events.html: • 1956 – The Romanian Television network begins its first broadcast in Bucharest.

events.description: RTÉ, Ireland's state broadcaster, launches its first national television service.
events.html: • 1961 – RTÉ, Ireland's state broadcaster, launches its first national television service.

events.description: The Central African Federation officially collapses, subsequently becoming Zambia, Malawi and Rhodesia.
events.html: • 1963 – The Central African Federation officially collapses, subsequently becoming Zambia, Malawi and Rhodesia.

events.description: The first flight of the Tupolev Tu-144, the first civilian supersonic transport in the world.
events.html: • 1968 – The first flight of the Tupolev Tu-144, the first civilian supersonic transport in the world.

events.description: MacRobertson Miller Airlines Flight 1750 crashes near Port Hedland, Western Australia, killing all 26 people on board.
events.html: • 1968 – MacRobertson Miller Airlines Flight 1750 crashes near Port Hedland, Western Australia, killing all 26 people on board.[20]

events.description: A coup d'état in Ghana removes President Hilla Limann's PNP government and replaces it with the Provisional National Defence Council led by Flight lieutenant Jerry Rawlings.

events.description: Benjamin Ward is appointed New York City Police Department's first ever African American police commissioner.
events.html: • 1983 – Benjamin Ward is appointed New York City Police Department's first ever African American police commissioner.

events.html: • 1983 – In Nigeria, a coup d'état led by Major General Muhammadu Buhari ends the Second Nigerian Republic.

events.description: All official Soviet Union institutions have ceased operations by this date, five days after the Soviet Union is officially dissolved.
events.html: • 1991 – All official Soviet Union institutions have ceased operations by this date, five days after the Soviet Union is officially dissolved.

events.description: Czechoslovakia is peacefully dissolved in what is dubbed by media as the Velvet Divorce, resulting in the creation of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.
events.html: • 1992 – Czechoslovakia is peacefully dissolved in what is dubbed by media as the Velvet Divorce, resulting in the creation of the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic.

events.description: This date is skipped altogether in Kiribati as the Phoenix Islands and Line Islands change time zones from UTC−11:00 to UTC+13:00 and UTC−10:00 to UTC+14:00, respectively.
events.html: • 1994 – This date is skipped altogether in Kiribati as the Phoenix Islands and Line Islands change time zones from UTC−11:00 to UTC+13:00 and UTC−10:00 to UTC+14:00, respectively.

events.description: The First Chechen War: The Russian Ground Forces begin a New Year's storming of Grozny.
events.html: • 1994 – The First Chechen War: The Russian Ground Forces begin a New Year's storming of Grozny.

events.description: The final comic of Calvin and Hobbes is published.
events.html: • 1995 – The final comic of Calvin and Hobbes is published.[21]

events.description: The European Exchange Rate Mechanism freezes the values of the legacy currencies in the Eurozone, and establishes the value of the euro currency.
events.html: • 1998 – The European Exchange Rate Mechanism freezes the values of the legacy currencies in the Eurozone, and establishes the value of the euro currency.

events.description: The first President of Russia, Boris Yeltsin, resigns from office, leaving Prime Minister Vladimir Putin as the acting President and successor.
events.html: • 1999 – The first President of Russia, Boris Yeltsin, resigns from office, leaving Prime Minister Vladimir Putin as the acting President and successor.

events.description: The U.S. government hands control of the Panama Canal (as well all the adjacent land to the canal known as the Panama Canal Zone) to Panama. This act complied with the signing of the 1977 Torrijos–Carter Treaties.
events.html: • 1999 – The U.S. government hands control of the Panama Canal (as well all the adjacent land to the canal known as the Panama Canal Zone) to Panama. This act complied with the signing of the 1977 Torrijos–Carter Treaties.

events.description: Indian Airlines Flight 814 hijacking ends after seven days with the release of 190 survivors at Kandahar Airport, Afghanistan.
events.html: • 1999 – Indian Airlines Flight 814 hijacking ends after seven days with the release of 190 survivors at Kandahar Airport, Afghanistan.
